<article id="post-412" class="post-412 page type-page status-publish hentry">

	                <figure>
                  
                </figure>    
            
	<div class="post-content">
		<h2 class="entry-title">Issues</h2> 
		<div class="entry-content">
			
<p>My name is Paul Lott.  I have lived and raised a family in Northern Virginia for much of my adult life.  My children have attended public school and college here, married, and raised their families here.  My activism started with the fight against Critical Race Theory because I have seen the damage to families who have embraced this destructive ideology. I have been active in politics for decades writing policy papers and supporting conservative candidates for 25 years. </p>



<p>I was once a Democrat in my early 20 years. My time in the military opened my eyes to the harmful policies pushed by the Democratic party. My values, like many Black Americans, are very conservative. I realized that the Democrat party did not represent my values and so I became a conservative Republic and convinced much of my extended family to do so as well. </p>



<p>Make no mistake. Freedom is on the ballot this election. The threat to our freedom has moved from the state house into our living rooms where the government wants to teach our children values that conflict with basic family values and morality. The U.S. Constitution states that the purpose of the Constitution is to &#8220;&#8230;secure the blessings of liberty for ourselves and our posterity.&#8221; In other words, our government was founded to secure the blessings of freedom for us and our families.  The Bill of Rights in the Virginia constitution states &#8220;That all power is vested in, and consequently derived from the people, that magistrates are their trustees and servants, and at all times amenable to them.&#8221; It seems our current leaders no longer believe that. I am running to give the power back to the people starting with parents</p>



<p>I support parental rights. I believe that men and women are uniquely different and that men should not be allowed to compete in women&#8217;s sports or use women&#8217;s facilities. Our schools should focus on academics, art, and sports. Social engineering is destroying our schools and destroying the nuclear family. I am strongly pro-life. In New York City more Black children are aborted than born live. That is wrong. Increased street violence is a symptom of America&#8217;s growing disregard for the sanctity of life. We need safe schools and safe streets. In order to protect our rights, we have to protect the integrity of our elections.</p>



<p>I will fight for our freedom if elected to the House of Delegates.</p>



<div id="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-0d97ee3d" class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion exclusive">
<details class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item"><summary class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item__title"><div><strong>Parents&#8217; Rights</strong></div></summary><div class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item__content">
<div class="wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile" style="grid-template-columns:47% auto"><figure class="wp-block-media-text__media"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="680" src="https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Family-1024x680.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-413 size-full" srcset="https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Family-1024x680.jpg 1024w, https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Family-768x510.jpg 768w, https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Family-1536x1019.jpg 1536w, https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Family.jpg 1701w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure><div class="wp-block-media-text__content">
<div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container">
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">I Support Parents&#8217; Rights</h2>
</div></div>



<figure class="wp-block-pullquote"><blockquote><p>&#8220;A parent has a fundamental right to make decisions concerning the upbringing, education, and care of the parent&#8217;s child.&#8221;</p><cite>&#8211; Virginia Code 1.240.1 Rights of Parents</cite></blockquote></figure>



<p>Virginia code clearly states that parents have the right to make decisions concerning the education of their children. In practice, we see county schools all over the Commonwealth implementing policies and programs that openly violate those rights. </p>



<p>The Virginia Legislature needs to expand the law to explicitly enumerate the rights of parents. Paul supports:</p>



<ul>
<li>Laws to remove objectionable material from schools or, at least, bar children from accessing this material without the written permission of their parents. </li>



<li>Laws barring schools from hiding any discussion regarding sex or sexuality from parents.</li>



<li>Laws barring a child from undergoing ANY medical procedure or taking any medicine without the permission of the parent.</li>



<li>Laws that bar teaching or implementing any social justice ideology, including critical race theory, in public schools or any government-funded program.</li>
</ul>



<p>The sanctity of the family must be preserved at all costs. Government overreach into the parent-child relationship is the single most dangerous issue facing Virginian families. </p>



<p></p>
</div></div>



<p></p>
</div></details>



<details class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item"><summary class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item__title"><div><strong>Women&#8217;s Rights</strong></div></summary><div class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item__content">
<div class="wp-block-media-text alignwide has-media-on-the-right is-stacked-on-mobile"><div class="wp-block-media-text__content">
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Males Should Not Be Allowed To Participate in Female Sports or Facilities or Vis Versa</h2>



<div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container">
<figure class="wp-block-pullquote"><blockquote><p>That no person shall be deprived of his life, liberty, or property without due process of law; that the General Assembly shall not pass any law impairing the obligation of contracts; and that the right to be free from any governmental discrimination upon the basis of religious conviction, race, color, sex, or national origin shall not be abridged, <mark style="background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)" class="has-inline-color has-vivid-red-color">except that the mere separation of the sexes shall not be considered discrimination.</mark></p><cite>&#8211; Virginia Constitution.  Section 11. Due process of law; obligation of contracts; taking or damaging of private property; prohibited discrimination; jury trial in civil cases.</cite></blockquote></figure>
</div></div>



<p>The Virginia Constitution clearly states that the separation of the sexes does NOT constitute discrimination for the purposes of Virginia law. </p>



<p>Virginia needs to pass laws that immediately ban:</p>



<ul>
<li>Males from participating in female sports.</li>



<li>Females from participating in Male sports.</li>



<li>From males using female locker rooms or bathrooms.</li>



<li>Females from using male locker rooms or bathrooms. </li>
</ul>
</div><figure class="wp-block-media-text__media"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="768" src="https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/01-teachers-rx-1-1024x768.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-415 size-full" srcset="https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/01-teachers-rx-1-1024x768.jpg 1024w, https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/01-teachers-rx-1-768x576.jpg 768w, https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/01-teachers-rx-1-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/01-teachers-rx-1.jpg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure></div>
</div></details>



<details class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item"><summary class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item__title"><div><strong>School Choice</strong></div></summary><div class="wp-block-themeisle-blocks-accordion-item__content">
<div class="wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile"><figure class="wp-block-media-text__media"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="683" src="https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/classroom-1024x683.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-416 size-full" srcset="https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/classroom-1024x683.jpeg 1024w, https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/classroom-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://paullottfordelegate.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/classroom.jpeg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure><div class="wp-block-media-text__content">
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">School Choice Is Critical to Improving Education</h2>



<p>Children get a quality education when parents take the lead in their children&#8217;s education. Parents know what is best for their children far more than a government school. It is the role of the government is to provide resources to give parents more options on how to best educate their children. The Virginia Department of Education should provide resources to all parents including those who choose homeschooling, public school, and private school.</p>



<p>Virginia needs to pass laws that:</p>



<ul>
<li>Offer Education Savings Accounts that enable parents to use a portion of their tax money to invest in non-public options for their children.</li>



<li>Offer sports participation to families regardless of whether their child attends homeschooling, public school, or private school. This builds community.</li>



<li>Funds every school district to have at least one public elementary, middle, and high school that offers a year-round academic calendar.</li>



<li>Expands the number of charter schools on a merit basis where charter schools are evaluated every two years for progress. Schools that show the greatest academic improvement should be offered the opportunity to take over the contracts of the least performing schools to ensure that the best schools are rewarded. Ideas that work to improve academic outcomes should be shared across all education providers.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>



<p></p>
</div></details>
</div>
